By taking square roots, we get \[\sqrt{(x-3)^2-(x-8)^2} = |x-3| - |x-8|.\]There are three cases to consider: \[x < 3,\] \[3 \le x \le 8,\] and \[x > 8.\]For each case, there is exactly one value of $x$ for which the function takes positive values. Because we are looking for the minimum of the function, we look for the minimum over each case. Then, to get our answer, we add the minimums.  For $x < 3,$ the function is equal to $3 - (x-8) = 11 - x.$ Since $11 - x > 0$ for all real $x,$ the minimum is 11 when $x < 3.$  For $3 \le x \le 8,$ the function is equal to $(x-3) - (x-8) = 5,$ so the minimum in this case is $5.$  Finally, for $x > 8,$ the function is equal to $(x-3) - (8-x) = 2x - 11.$ Since $2x - 11 < 0$ for all real $x > 8,$ the minimum in this case is $-\infty.$  Adding the three minimums, we get $\boxed{11}.$  (If you can see this answer without doing any actual arithmetic, you should use that to speed up your answer!) odenseer
