For each prime $p\ne 2$, $\gcd(8, p) = 1$. By Fermat's Little Theorem, $8^{\phi(p)} \equiv 1 \pmod p$ for all primes $p\ne 2$, so $x = 8^{\phi(p)} \pmod{p}$ satisfies $8x\equiv 1 \pmod p$ iff $8^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1^{\phi(p)} = 1 \pmod p$. This gives the equation $x^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1 \pmod p$, or that $x = \pm 1 \pmod p$. Since $p\geq 5$ is prime, $1\ne \pm 1\pmod p$, so $8$ has a solution iff $p\leq 2$. If $p=2$, then $8$ has no solution, which gives us $p=2$ as one prime which satisfies the given condition. If $p\geq 3$ is prime, then we must have $8^{\phi(p)} = 1^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1 \pmod p$, which means $p$ must be prime. If $p\geq 7$, we have \begin{align*}
2^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1 \pmod{p}
\end{align*} and \begin{align*}
8^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1^{\phi(p)}\equiv 1 \pmod p.
\end{align*}This gives us that $p = 2$ or $p$ is prime. However, $p = 2$ is not prime, so all the primes that give no solutions are 2.

Since $2$ is the only prime in our answer, the sum of all such primes is $\boxed{2}$.

